			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Updating 208 tiles plus attributes in one vblank is possible with early-off or late-on.<br /><br />In 32x32, it's possible to animate 12 or 16 tiles at once using scroll splits, where the background represents two columns of tiles moving at the same velocity and the sprites represent tiles that <em>aren't</em> moving at the same velocity. Do I need to illustrate this with another animation?<br /><br />But in practice, did people who played <em>Dr. Mario</em> care that everything moved in 8-pixel jumps? If not, lack of &quot;proper fluidity of animation&quot; is no deal-killer.<br /><br />I'm not trying to say that there's no place for a game using 16x16 pixel tiles. But something simulating <a href="http://www.folklore.org/StoryView.py?project=Macintosh&amp;story=Puzzle.txt" class="postlink">desk accessories</a> is probably better in a faux-windowed environment, like <a href="http://www.cracked.com/blog/the-7-least-necessary-pirated-video-games_p2/" class="postlink">Windows 98 for NES</a>, not in a traditional full-screen environment.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

